posts.name: Daniel Raygoza
posts.cooked:
Since I’m new to ChiefDelphi most the gifs will be on separate posts below this probably. :[

NVIDIA Omniverse is a tool used for robotics simulation and synthetic data generation. I believe it does have some practical use cases in FRC for quickly getting AI Models from data that would usually exist on full FRC Field that some people might not have access to. In the future I’ll likely experiment to see how good it is for simulating robots for my dream goal of a fully autonomous robot .

You can generate synthetic data in various formats to do things such as

Object pose estimation with DOPE (Deep Object Pose Estimation)

Object detection through various methods such as YOLO

vSLAM

So much more

Note: the rest of this is kinda a very very bare-bones tutorial if you’re looking at seeing what you can do and getting started

For some prerequisites you should look here

To get started you have to install the Omniverse Launcher, then you’ll have to install Isaac Sim, and I think that version 4.1.0 is a little bit better just because of a bug in 4.2.0 that might make it hard to make custom materials. Even though you’ll likely need some programming experience in python, if you have experience in any other language it’ll likely not be too difficult for the light amount of code in python that you might write.

Here you can drag a model of various potential fields to test the game on for me I wanted to play around with generating synthetic data for a real field for 2025, so after importing the Reefscape Field model I had to play around with the materials (and still do a bit to get the most authentic feel)

Then I selected all the coral and all the algae and gave them semantics so when generating synthetic data it’ll know what is what.

Then in a folder in vscode I created a little workspace that I called reefscape_sim which has a .vscode/ folder that is fairly close to the one in C:\Users\*user*\AppData\Local\ov\pkg\isaac-sim-4.1.0\.vscode with some slight modifications so that I can have intellisense while I’m working.

posts.name: Sam
posts.cooked: Hey, that’s pretty cool!  I saw that you posted a gif of how the model ended up working, but have you done any more real-world testing?  Also, how does the data compare to real-world data?  I know in real-world applications, there’s likely going to be a lot more variance in terms of lighting conditions, so I’m wondering if that’s going to be account for here.  I’m also creating a dataset of pictures on roboflow that you might be interested in.

posts.name: Daniel Raygoza
posts.cooked:
I only created a fairly small sample size for the model in which I also didn’t yet add images by variation (brightness, rotation, etc…), so there’s still quite a bit of progress that I could make. I can say that it will almost definitely work IRL, although I’m still likely gonna have to experiment with it more when I have the time.

The great thing about Omniverse is that you can always add more code to randomize things even further. Various types of lighting, obscure camera angles, cameraFocusDistance, cameraFocalLength, cameraAperture, the materials of any object, you can randomize the environment to instead of a normal field you could have any object in a factory, hospital, office, etc… you could sprinkle in a variety of misc. props. Although you can also add various humans into your scene I think that it’ll likely be better through real data just because programmatically posing humans might be strange although I haven’t played with it too much yet. TLDR: Omniverse has the ability to programmatically change pretty much anything to create a large variety of photos

I think where Omniverse really excels is by allowing you to capture more than just a bounding box of the object. For instance they have a way to accurately detect the pose of an object using Deep Object Pose Estimation or CenterPose, which might be better for exacting the position of things, which could include robots and game pieces. Moreover there’s just some things that those who don’t have a real field won’t be able to get many images of. Looking at The Zebracorns (Team 900). I think they use some sort of SLAM localization, so being able to track any element on the field might be helpful there.
